{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χᾰρίζω</b>, <br /> <i>future</i> χαριῶ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.381 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, “Corpus Glossariorum Latinorum” \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> <i>imperative</i> χάρισον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PMag.Lond.” 122.17 \">Refs</a>]:—usually <i>middle</i> <b>χαρίζομαι</b>, <i>future</i> <b>-ιοῦμαι</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.40, 8.65 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; χαριῇ (variant{-εῖ}) also in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.90; Cretan dialect χαριξίομαι “GDI” 5176.16 (found at Teos); also χαρίξομαι [prev. work]5178.17 ([prev. passage]); χαρίηνται\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] is a false <i>Aeolic dialect</i> form in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Milet.” 3 No.152.56; later χαρίσομαι NT.Rom.8.32, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “DDeor.” 22.4 \">NT+2nd c.AD+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἐχαρισάμην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.91, etc.; _optative_ χαρίσαιτο 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.49 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <i>imperative</i> χάρισσαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 16.4 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; Cretan dialect <i>infinitive</i> χαρίξασθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “GDI” 5163b8 (from Mylasa):\">Refs</a>] —<i>passive</i> forms, <i>future</i> χαρισθήσομαι in <i>passive</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Philm.22: \">NT</a>]<i>aorist</i> ἐχαρίσθην in <i>passive</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Act.3.14, NT.1Cor.2.12: \">NT</a>]<i>perfect</i> κεχάρισμαι in <i>active</i> sense, κεχάρισαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 1045\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <b>-ισται</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. author] “Eq.” 54 \">Refs</a>]; also in <i>passive</i> sense, <i>imperative</i> <b>-ίσθω</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 250c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ἐκεχάριστο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>Epic dialect</i> κεχάριστο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.23 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>say</b> or <b>do something agreeable</b> to a person, <b>show</b> him <b>favour</b> or <b>kindness, oblige, gratify,</b> with <i>dative</i> <i>person</i>, frequently in <i>participle</i>, χαριζομένη πόσεϊ ᾧ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.71, compare 11.23, 15.449, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.538, 13.265; once in 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus, ποίησε.. χαριζόμενος Διί “Th.” 580; πᾶσι χαριζοίμην ἄν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.130, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.40; τοῖς θεοῖς 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 4.3.16 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; Καλλίᾳ χαριζόμενος <b>to oblige, humour</b> him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 362a, compare “Men.” 75b, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 1368 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of a judge, give a <b>partial</b> verdict, χ. οἷς ἂν δοκῇ αὐτῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 35c; also χ. τῷ ἵππῳ 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “de Equitandi ratione” 10.12 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>absolutely</i>, <b>make oneself agreeable, comply,</b> opposed to ἀντία φάσθαι, once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus, “Pers.” 700 (Lyric poetry); οἱ ὑπὲρ καιρὸν χαριζόμενοι 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 4.7: with _accusative_ _cognate_, χάριτας χ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 360.1, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 1.31, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.239; χ. τι καὶ αὐτός 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.42 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; with <i>participle</i> added, χαρίζετο ἱερὰ ῥέζων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.61, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.90, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 1045, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 338a, 426c, etc.: more frequently with _dative_ modi, μήτε τί μοι ψεύδεσσι χαρίζεο\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>do</b> not <b>court favour</b> by lies, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.387; χαριζόμενος φιλότητι 10.43, etc.; λόγῳ θωπεῦσαι καὶ ἔργῳ χ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 173a codices \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to τὰ βέλτιστα λέγειν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 9.2, compare 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.66a. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>gratify</b> or <b>indulge</b> a humour or passion, once in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, θυμῷ χαρίζεσθαι κενά “El.” 331, compare 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 4.3.2, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 7.1.25; ὀργῇ 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 31; γλώσσῃ [prev. author] “Or.” 1514 (troch.); ἔρωτι 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 127; τῇ ἐπιθυμίᾳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 561c: τῷ σώματι 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.2.23 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τῇ γαστρί[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 2.1.2, “Cyr.” 4.2.39; τῇ ἡδονῇ [prev. work] 4.3.2. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> in erotic sense, <b>grant favours</b> to a man, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 629 (_anapaest meter_), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 182a, “Phdr.” 231c, 256a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 3.11.12, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: hence of Comedy, ὀλίγοις χαρίσασθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 517 (_anapaest meter_): with _accusative_ _cognate_, χ. θήλειαν ἀπόλαυσιν 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Am.” 27. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> with <i>accusative</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>give graciously</b> or <b>cheerfully,</b> δῶρα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 24.283; ἄποινα 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.49, 10.380; χαρίζεσθαί τινί τι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.91, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 437, “Eq.” 54, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 1.4.9, etc.; πωλεῖν καὶ χ. καὶ τέκνοις μεταδιδόναι “PGrenf.” 1.60.45 (6th c.AD)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; so with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i>, χαρίζομαί σε τοῖς ὄχλοις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PFlor.” 61.61 (1st c.AD)\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: with a strong oxymoron, ξείνια δυσμενέσιν λυγρὰ χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 7 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i> with <i>Article</i>, χ. τὸ ποθεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.609a; τὸ ζῆν LXX.2Mac.3.33 \">LXX+1st c.AD+</a>]; without the <i>Article</i>, πολλοῖς ἐχαρίσατο βλέπειν (variant{τὸ β}.) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Luke.7.21 \">NT</a>]; χάρισαι [αὐτοῖς] μένειν <b>allow</b> them to remain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Am.” 19, compare “Anthologia Graeca” 5.236 (6th c.AD: Agathias Historicus et Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; so ἆρ᾽ ἄν τί μοι χαρίσαιο τοιόνδε—μή μου καταγελᾶ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Hp.Mi.” 364c. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.b</b></Level4> χ. τὴν δέησιν <b>grant</b> the request, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Bis Acc.” 14. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__II.c</b></Level4> <i>passive</i>, with <i>accusative</i>, <b>to be favoured with,</b> ἀνάγκᾳ πνεῦμα χαριζόμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “epigram Gr.” 204.18 (from Cnidus). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> with <i>genitive</i> <i>partitive</i>, <b>give freely of</b> a thing, ἀλλοτρίων χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 17.452 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ταμίη.. χαριζομένη παρεόντων <b>giving freely of</b> such things as were ready, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.140 \">Refs</a>], etc.; παντοίων ἀγαθῶν γαστρὶ χαριζόμενοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 1000; γλώσσης μαφιδίοιο χ. παρεοῦσι 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 25.188 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; προικὸς χαρίζεσθαι, of his bounty, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.15. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i>, <b>give up as a favour,</b> τῇ μητρὶ χ. Ὀκτάβιον, by dropping a law aimed at him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “C. Gracchus” 4 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; but also, by unjust condemnation, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Act.25.11, 16 \">NT</a>]; also τῷ θεῷ με ἐχαρίσω, of a <b>dedication</b> ceremony, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PBremen” 49.14 (2nd c.AD). \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>forgive,</b> τὴν ἀδικίαν τινί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.2Cor.12.13, cf. NT.Col.2.13: _absolutely_, NT.2Cor.2.7, etc. \">NT</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>passive</i>, especially in <i>perfect</i> and <i>pluperfect</i>, κεχάριστο θυμῷ <b>was dear</b> to her heart, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.23 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τοῖσι Εὐβοεῦσι ἐκεχάριστο the <b>pleasure</b> of the Euboeans <b>was done,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ταῦτα μὲν οὖν μνήμῃ κεχαρίσθω <b>let a tribute be paid</b>.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 250c; compare χάρις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus V. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> mostly <i>participle</i> <i>perfect</i> κεχαρισμένος, η, ον, as <i>adjective</i>, <b>acceptable, welcome,</b> ἐμῷ κεχαρισμένε θυμῷ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.243, 826, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κεχαρισμένα δῶρα θεοῖσι δίδωσι,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 20.298, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 16.184, 19.397 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κεχαρισμένα θεῖναί τινι to do <b>things pleasing</b> to one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 24.661; ἀνὴρ κεχαρισμένα εἰδώς 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.584; θεοις κεχαρισμένα ποιεῖν 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 6.33 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κεχ. τοῖς θεοῖς λέγειν τε καὶ πράττειν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 14b, compare “Phdr.” 273e; δοίη ᾧ κ᾽ ἐθέλοι καί οἱ κεχαρισμένος ἔλθοι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.54, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.87, 3.119, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.2.10, etc.; κεχαρισμένα θύρσῳ 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 892 (Lyric poetry); κεχαρ. χοιρίδιον 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 386 (Lyric poetry); πᾶσιν κεχαρισμένος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 218a; λόγος κεχ. 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 14.1; σιτίον ἢ ποτόν 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.24; ἐν τοῖς μὴ κεχαρισμένοις.. πρὸς τὴν αἴσθησιν 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Partibus Animalium” 645a7 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; compare κεχαρισμένως. <br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> later, <i>comparative</i> κεχαρισμενώτερος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 12.7 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; <i>superlative</i> <b>-ώτατος</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Alciphro Epistolographus 3.65.\">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>] —Rare in Trag., but frequently in _Attic dialect_ Prose.","strongNumber":"G5483","accentedUnicode":"χαρίζω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0884","matchingForm":"ἀχάριστος","stepTransliteration":"acharistos","gloss":"ungrateful","_zh_tw_Gloss":"忘恩","_es_Gloss":"ingrato","_zh_Gloss":"忘恩"},{"strongNumber":"G5485","matchingForm":"χάρις","stepTransliteration":"charis","gloss":"grace","_zh_tw_Gloss":"恩典","_es_Gloss":"gracia","_zh_Gloss":"恩典"},{"strongNumber":"G5486","matchingForm":"χάρισμα","stepTransliteration":"charisma","gloss":"gift","_zh_tw_Gloss":"恩賜","_es_Gloss":"don","_zh_Gloss":"恩赐"}],"shortDef":"to give grace; to forgive, cancel (a debt); to grant; to hand over into custody","mediumDef":"to give grace; to forgive, cancel (a debt); to grant; to hand over into custody <br /><b>to gratify; to bestow</b>, in kindness, <b>grant</b> as a free favor, <ref='Luk.7.21'>Lk. 7:21</ref>; <ref='Rom.8.32'>Rom. 8:32;</ref> <b>to grant the deliverance</b> of a person in favor to the desire of others, <ref='Act.3.14'>Acts 3:14;</ref> 27:24; Phlm. 22; <b>to sacrifice</b> a person to the demand of enemies, <ref='Act.25.11'>Acts 25:11;</ref> <b>to remit, forgive,</b> <ref='Luk.7.42'>Lk. 7:42</ref>; <ref='2Co.2.7, 10'>2Cor. 2:7, 10</ref>","stepGloss":"to give grace","stepTransliteration":"charizō","count":23,"_es_Definition":"otorgar, dar, conceder; tratar generosa o bondadosamente con, perdonar ; entregar o liberar (un prisionero) ; perdonar una deuda (LUC.7:42,43) ; ser devuelto (FLM.1:22)","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 惠施(白白給予)<br>2) 取消債務 (路 7:42)<br>3) 赦罪,寬恕","_zh_Definition":"1) 惠施(白白给予)<br>2) 取消债务 (路 7:42)<br>3) 赦罪,宽恕","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"tha thứ; lệnh ân xá","_zh_tw_Gloss":"赦免","_es_Gloss":"dar gracia","_zh_Gloss":"赦免"}]}